00:02:19.160 --> 00:02:21.350
So as Janet mentioned,
I'm going to be talking

00:02:21.350 --> 00:02:24.050
about the epidemiology of
neurological and psychiatric

00:02:24.050 --> 00:02:26.930
disorders, and I wanted
to start with just

00:02:26.930 --> 00:02:30.745
going through what I see as the
big questions in this field.

00:02:30.745 --> 00:02:32.870
And these are probably not
unlike the big questions

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:36.060
in any sort of subfield
of epidemiology.

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:39.590
So we want to know, how many
people suffer from dementia?

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:42.290
Who is at highest risk
of bipolar disorder?

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:44.270
How can we prevent
schizophrenia?

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:46.190
How can we treat depression?

00:02:46.190 --> 00:02:48.170
How can we reduce the
negative consequences

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:49.940
of eating disorders?

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:51.740
And so these are the
big kinds of questions

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:54.154
that motivated me to
get into epidemiology,

00:02:54.154 --> 00:02:56.570
and the kinds of questions
that underlie a lot of the work

00:02:56.570 --> 00:03:00.692
that I do and my colleagues
do across the world.

00:03:00.692 --> 00:03:02.900
However, a lot of the work--
as Janet kind of alluded

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.330
to already-- that I work
on is actually also getting

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:06.650
into the methods of this.

00:03:06.650 --> 00:03:09.680
So not just how do we answer
these questions, but how

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:10.920
do we answer them better.

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:14.610
How do we improve the ways
that we answer these questions.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:17.270
I didn't want this to be a
very mathematical talk, though,

00:03:17.270 --> 00:03:19.895
so what I'm going to do is kind
of go through a little bit more

00:03:19.895 --> 00:03:23.560
of the philosophy of doing
that in a sound manner.

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:25.490
And in particular, I
want to try to walk us

00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:29.340
through a couple of steps
in this scientific process.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.120
So how do we start with one
of those really big questions

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:34.180
and try to tackle that?

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:36.680
And what we want to do is we
have to distill it down to some

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:40.460
more precise, more manageable,
but still quite relevant

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:41.750
questions.

00:03:41.750 --> 00:03:44.210
And once we have a more
precise question stated,

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:46.430
we can go on to collect
and analyze data,

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:49.340
to obtain some answer
to that question,

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:51.290
and then discuss
the results of that

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:53.450
as transparently as we can.

00:03:53.450 --> 00:03:55.820
Now the last up iteration
I just want to underscore

00:03:55.820 --> 00:03:57.170
is really important here.

00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.160
Science is a process.

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:01.340
It's not an end
result. I'm not going

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:03.460
to talk as much about the
iteration part of this,

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:06.230
but I just want us to be mindful
that this sometimes means going

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:08.210
back up to that big question.

00:04:08.210 --> 00:04:10.510
Sometimes refining
our sub-question,

00:04:10.510 --> 00:04:14.220
sometimes collecting new
data, sometimes re-analyzing

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:18.070
and reinterpreting the
results of that data.

00:04:18.070 --> 00:04:20.760
And so what I'm going to do
is go through this process

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.950
together with two
questions that I've kind of

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:24.880
worked with in my research.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:26.610
And the first big
question I want to ask

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:29.100
is just, how many
adolescents in the US

00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:30.630
actually have an
eating disorder?

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:35.560
How would we try to obtain an
estimate for this question?

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:38.639
Now before I go into making
that a more precise question,

00:04:38.639 --> 00:04:40.180
I want to give just
a little bit more

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.280
background on eating
disorders for those that

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:44.290
are less familiar with them.

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:47.140
So traditionally, there were
two types of eating disorders

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:50.650
that were recognized by
medical professionals, anorexia

00:04:50.650 --> 00:04:52.384
and bulimia nervosa.

00:04:52.384 --> 00:04:53.800
There's specific
criteria that you

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:57.194
need to meet in order to get a
diagnosis of either of these.

00:04:57.194 --> 00:04:59.110
I'm not going to go
through all the specifics,

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:01.210
but essentially anorexia
is characterized

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:03.430
by this low weight,
fear of weight gain,

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:05.620
and a disturbance in how
one experiences their shape

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:06.860
and weight.

00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:10.300
Whereas bulimia is characterized
by having binge eating,

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:12.790
so overeating with
loss of control,

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:17.290
and compensatory behaviors
such as self-induced vomiting.

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:20.830
More recently there was another
eating disorder recognized,

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:23.560
a binge eating disorder, and
then everything else kind of

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:26.890
falls under this other category,
this catchall, not otherwise

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:30.610
specified diagnosis for
eating disorders that don't

00:05:30.610 --> 00:05:33.370
meet these strict criteria.

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:36.029
So one thing to keep in mind
is that with eating disorders

00:05:36.029 --> 00:05:38.320
the majority of patients that
present for care actually

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:42.800
fall under this not
otherwise specified category.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.560
So with that in mind, let's
go back to our big question--

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:48.104
how many adolescents in the
US have an eating disorder--

00:05:48.104 --> 00:05:49.520
and try to distill
it to some more

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:51.900
precise manageable questions.

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:54.770
And here I think it's important
to think through our motivation

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:57.420
for asking that question
in the first place.

00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:59.690
So one possible
motivation is that we're

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:03.170
trying to get some estimate
at how many individuals would

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:05.490
benefit from some sort of care.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:07.250
And this is already
sort of fuzzy.

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:09.390
This is not a precise
enough question yet,

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:10.790
but this gets at
the idea that we

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:13.640
might want to know about any
eating disorder, or maybe even

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:15.730
anyone with a symptom
of an eating disorder.

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:18.230
And that's the kind of number
that we're kind of setting out

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:20.066
to get.

00:06:20.066 --> 00:06:21.440
Another possibility
is that we're

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:23.570
interested in getting the
proportion of individuals

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:25.220
with one of the
specific subtypes

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:27.810
or a couple different
listed subtypes.

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:30.410
So we might want to know how
many have anorexia or bulimia,

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:32.540
for example.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:35.374
And then finally, another reason
we might be motivated for this

00:06:35.374 --> 00:06:36.790
is that we're
trying to understand

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:40.150
how to allocate resources
for care as it's currently

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:41.172
being sought.

00:06:41.172 --> 00:06:42.880
And in this case, we
wouldn't necessarily

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:44.620
want to know how
many individuals

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:49.130
have an eating disorder, but
how many seek treatment for it.

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:50.589
So when I put
these side by side,

00:06:50.589 --> 00:06:52.880
hopefully it's obvious that
they're different questions

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:55.070
and we're going to get
different answers to them.

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:56.540
And that'd be true
if we did this

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:58.190
with any other
psychiatric disorder.

00:06:58.190 --> 00:07:00.650
That'd be true if we did
this with cancer, with HIV,

00:07:00.650 --> 00:07:02.710
or anything else.

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:04.840
One of the challenges in
psychiatric disorders,

00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:06.940
though, is that there
can be huge differences

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:09.130
between these three questions.

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:11.620
That's a very different
issue between A and B

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.690
there because of
these fuzzy boundaries

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:16.300
of what the definitions
of our disorders are,

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:18.430
and there's a huge
difference between B and C

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:20.110
because there's
a lot of barriers

00:07:20.110 --> 00:07:25.820
to treatment like stigma, having
a lack of insurance coverage,

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:27.370
and so on.

00:07:27.370 --> 00:07:28.750
And so actually
in work that I've

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:30.708
done trying to answer
these questions with some

00:07:30.708 --> 00:07:34.150
of my colleagues, we get
very different estimates.

00:07:34.150 --> 00:07:37.900
We'd say that something like 1
in 10 for the first question,

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:41.170
1 in 100 for the second
question, and one in 1,000

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:42.250
for the third.

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:46.670
So just absolutely
enormous differences here.

00:07:46.670 --> 00:07:49.062
Now, again, you might say,
of course they're different.

00:07:49.062 --> 00:07:50.270
I see that they're different.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:52.710
This is the end
of the story here.

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:54.500
But part of the
process of science

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:56.660
is understanding where
these numbers get used

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:58.840
for the next question we ask.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.860
So if we're asking
who is at highest risk

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:02.630
for eating disorder,
it's important

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:04.190
that we know which
kind of category

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:07.880
we're starting to dissect from.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:11.180
In particular, if we turn to
research as it was historically

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.120
done in eating disorders,
most of the research

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:16.820
was done in just clinical
or specialty care settings.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.680
So they were only
recruiting patients

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:20.720
from these settings
who by definition were

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:22.287
seeking treatment.

00:08:22.287 --> 00:08:23.870
What this means is
that we were really

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:26.619
missing the full picture of
who is most vulnerable to have

00:08:26.619 --> 00:08:27.410
an eating disorder.

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:30.109
We were missing
out on who actually

00:08:30.109 --> 00:08:32.150
has an eating disorder,
because we were actually,

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:34.880
by definition, looking at who
is most likely to seek care

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:36.309
for it.

00:08:36.309 --> 00:08:37.850
And so what I want
to do next is just

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:39.710
go through some
misconceptions that

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:43.256
followed from that line of
research, and many of these

00:08:43.256 --> 00:08:44.630
are probably
familiar to you when

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:48.590
you think of the prototypical
eating disorder patient.

00:08:48.590 --> 00:08:51.590
So first, it's been
kind of long thought

00:08:51.590 --> 00:08:54.380
that eating disorders
don't affect males.

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:57.110
Indeed, when we look at
treatment seeking samples,

00:08:57.110 --> 00:08:58.880
it's almost a 10 to 1 ratio.

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:00.890
And this is such a
predominant belief

00:09:00.890 --> 00:09:02.970
that's quoted in most
medical textbooks.

00:09:02.970 --> 00:09:06.170
It's quoted in the
DSM, and this is really

00:09:06.170 --> 00:09:08.224
this propagated belief.

00:09:08.224 --> 00:09:10.390
When we look at some of the
community-based samples,

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:13.835
however, the ratio of females
to males is closer to two

00:09:13.835 --> 00:09:14.780
to three to one.

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:16.910
And for some of the
specific subtypes,

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:19.070
it's actually close to 1 to 1.

00:09:19.070 --> 00:09:21.330
So yes, they may affect
females more generally,

00:09:21.330 --> 00:09:23.540
but there's such a
bigger discrepancy

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:25.400
in terms of the
treatment-seeking numbers

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:29.150
than the
community-based numbers.

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:30.440
The same could be true--

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:34.790
said for minorities for
looking across Western cultures

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:36.500
versus non-western
cultures, looking

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:38.930
across socioeconomic status.

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:42.740
So when we look at who
actually in a community sample

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:45.470
meets criteria for
an eating disorder,

00:09:45.470 --> 00:09:47.180
there aren't as
big of differences

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:51.780
as we get in the
treatment-seeking samples.

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:54.240
And then finally, based on
treatment-seeking samples,

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:57.090
we tend to believe that
eating disorders onset in late

00:09:57.090 --> 00:09:59.260
adolescence or early adulthood.

00:09:59.260 --> 00:10:02.280
This is actually more
in line with when

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:04.710
they start seeking
care, but the symptoms

00:10:04.710 --> 00:10:06.925
may start occurring
many years before.

00:10:06.925 --> 00:10:08.550
And so this just
underscores that we're

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:11.370
missing an opportunity
to intervene much earlier

00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:14.640
in the process based on this
kind of misinterpretation

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:15.170
of the data.

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:19.400
Now another thing
to keep in mind

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:22.010
when we are trying to
refine our question

00:10:22.010 --> 00:10:24.020
is to think about when
we're asking about.

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.750
In particular, when we're
thinking about specific eating

00:10:26.750 --> 00:10:28.740
disorders subtypes.

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:30.950
So I know this is a
very colorful graph,

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:35.840
but just to orient you each row
represents a particular patient

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:38.480
who at the beginning of
the 12 year follow-up

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:41.910
met criteria for one
specific eating disorder.

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:45.260
And so if we look across just
one particular row, every time

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:47.210
we see the color
change in that row that

00:10:47.210 --> 00:10:50.570
means that the diagnosis that
we would give to that patient

00:10:50.570 --> 00:10:53.220
at that moment in
time would change.

00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:55.820
And so if you wanted to get an
estimate of how many patients

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:58.220
have anorexia in
this sample, you

00:10:58.220 --> 00:11:00.350
get very different estimates
if you looked at one

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:03.830
particular time, or if you
asked about their entire history

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:05.589
or just the past year.

00:11:05.589 --> 00:11:07.130
And so this is just
something we have

00:11:07.130 --> 00:11:10.160
to be mindful of when we're
asking these kinds of questions

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:12.050
is what is the precise
question that we're

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:13.760
trying to obtain from our data.

00:11:17.470 --> 00:11:19.690
So then let's go back
to our step-by-step.

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:22.480
We started with this
really big question,

00:11:22.480 --> 00:11:25.580
how many adolescents
have an eating disorder?

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:28.270
And one possible way that we
could distill this question

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:31.060
would be to ask, well, what
proportion of US adolescents

00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:34.891
have ever met criteria for
any eating disorder subtype?

00:11:34.891 --> 00:11:36.640
And then this, again,
is just one example.

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:38.470
There's lots of other
questions that we

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:41.140
could have asked as well.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:42.880
But with this question
in mind, then we

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:45.160
can think about collecting
data and analyzing

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:47.650
that data judiciously
to obtain our best

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:50.000
answer to that question.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.540
So I worked with the National
Co-morbidity Survey Adolescent

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:57.130
Supplement, which was a survey
of about 10,000 US adolescents.

00:11:57.130 --> 00:12:00.160
And in doing interviews on
different eating disorders,

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:03.850
we were able to obtain an
estimate of about 5% meeting

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:06.730
criteria for the
subtypes we measured.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.980
Now I say on the slide
there that that's

00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:10.946
sort of a lower bound
estimate, and that's

00:12:10.946 --> 00:12:12.820
because we were very
mindful that we couldn't

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:15.500
measure all types of subtypes.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.040
So when we discuss
the results, we've

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:20.590
made clear that we were only
getting certain subtypes.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:24.550
We were being very clear about
the quality of our measurements

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:26.257
and issues with
the measurements.

00:12:26.257 --> 00:12:28.090
But the point is that
we were putting it out

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.459
there as a dialogue
to keep on refining.

00:12:30.459 --> 00:12:32.500
And indeed, since then
there's been a lot of work

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:34.120
that I've been a
part of where we

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:35.800
are able to measure
some of the subtypes

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:38.350
that we didn't get and try
to get better triangulation

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:41.090
of these estimates.

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:44.780
So now I want to turn to a
different kind of big question,

00:12:44.780 --> 00:12:49.520
a causal question in a
sense, which is asking rather

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:52.520
than just trying to count who
has an eating disorder, who

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:55.400
meets criteria for these
different outcomes,

00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:56.970
we want to do
something about it.

00:12:56.970 --> 00:12:59.180
How could we prevent
an eating disorder?

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:01.760
How could we treat eating
disorders in our populations?

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:05.150
How could we reduce the
negative consequences of them?

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:06.770
And I'm not going
to boil this down

00:13:06.770 --> 00:13:08.520
to one specific
sub-question, but I

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:10.610
want to give just kind of
a feel of the philosophy

00:13:10.610 --> 00:13:15.614
of this causal inference
approach in these settings.

00:13:15.614 --> 00:13:17.030
So again, we're
going to try first

00:13:17.030 --> 00:13:23.100
to distill this down to a more
precise, relevant question.

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:26.554
And as we heard in the
previous session, ideally

00:13:26.554 --> 00:13:27.970
we would have our
causal questions

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:30.490
like this answered with
well-conducted, large,

00:13:30.490 --> 00:13:32.120
randomized trials.

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:33.790
So if we were
interested in looking

00:13:33.790 --> 00:13:36.370
at an anti-bullying
campaign in schools,

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:38.560
we would randomize
some schools to receive

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:41.950
that campaign, some schools to
not, and follow that over time

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:44.350
and see if mental health
improves in those schools.

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.780
If we're interested in some
treatment for depression

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:48.680
like a new therapy,
we'd want to randomize

00:13:48.680 --> 00:13:51.370
some patients to get it,
some patients to get standard

00:13:51.370 --> 00:13:52.330
of care--

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:57.870
follow them over time
and see what is going on.

00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:00.350
There's a lot of times, though,
where our questions are not

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:02.690
going to be feasibly
or ethically answered

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:04.010
with randomized trials.

00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:05.940
And, in fact, for a lot
of pressing questions,

00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:07.850
we also just don't want
to necessarily wait

00:14:07.850 --> 00:14:09.770
for those trials to happen.

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:11.510
It might take decades
before we really

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:14.450
learned the long term
consequences of what

00:14:14.450 --> 00:14:20.390
happens to a fetus prenatally,
just as one example.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:22.580
And so because of
this, we have to rely

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:23.754
on observational studies.

00:14:23.754 --> 00:14:25.670
And this comes back again
to some of the talks

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:28.670
that we heard earlier where
we have to somehow rely

00:14:28.670 --> 00:14:32.645
on having our causal inferences
based on observational data.

00:14:32.645 --> 00:14:34.520
What this means is that
we need to have a way

00:14:34.520 --> 00:14:37.760
to link or observe data
to causal questions.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.310
We need some sort of formal
mathematical language

00:14:40.310 --> 00:14:45.050
for saying why our observed data
is linked to these questions

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:46.882
that we're trying to ask.

00:14:46.882 --> 00:14:48.590
Now I don't want to
go into the specifics

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.340
of these different
mathematical languages.

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:52.210
There's a lot going on there.

00:14:52.210 --> 00:14:54.860
In fact, maybe that could be an
entire next in science series

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:58.480
is just all the languages
of causal inference.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:00.230
But one of the
commonalities that comes up

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:02.480
from really thinking
about these approaches

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:04.910
is that in order to
estimate a causal effect,

00:15:04.910 --> 00:15:07.482
you have to have a precise
idea of the definition

00:15:07.482 --> 00:15:08.690
that you're trying to obtain.

00:15:08.690 --> 00:15:11.360
You have to know what
that starting question was

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:13.324
as precisely as you can.

00:15:13.324 --> 00:15:14.990
Another way to think
of this is that you

00:15:14.990 --> 00:15:17.680
have to have a really good
idea of what the protocol is

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:20.840
of that hypothetical trial you
wish you could have conducted

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:24.060
and you're using the
observed data for instead.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:26.400
What we see is that if we
have ill-defined questions,

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:28.032
we end up with
ill-defined answers.

00:15:28.032 --> 00:15:29.490
And so to the extent
that we really

00:15:29.490 --> 00:15:33.240
do want to prevent eating
disorders from onsetting

00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:37.200
or treat them better or improve
the lives of the patients who

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.270
have it, it's really
fundamental that we

00:15:39.270 --> 00:15:43.380
start by making these
questions clear.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:46.220
So when we're thinking
about this step-by-step

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:48.060
and we're trying to
take this big question

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:50.390
and distill it down, I
think it's really important

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:52.490
that we're mindful of
how we're distilling

00:15:52.490 --> 00:15:56.120
this down to manageable
but very precise questions.

00:15:56.120 --> 00:15:58.580
So what is that target trial
that we're trying to do?

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:01.160
What is the protocol exactly?

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:02.870
And then once
we've done that, we

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:05.420
can think through how we're
going to collect and analyze

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:07.742
data to answer that question.

00:16:07.742 --> 00:16:09.200
And that might mean
doing something

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:11.900
like propensity score matching
or regression discontinuity

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:12.920
as we heard earlier.

00:16:12.920 --> 00:16:16.160
That could be many other
kinds of statistical methods.

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:18.800
But I think the other thing
we need to be mindful of

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:21.710
is that these questions
or these analyses

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:24.290
are always tied back
to that question--

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:26.690
that there should be a
link between the analysis

00:16:26.690 --> 00:16:29.240
we did and the question
that we're trying to ask.

00:16:29.240 --> 00:16:32.090
And otherwise, we're
losing this opportunity

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:34.119
where we have
counterproductive answers

00:16:34.119 --> 00:16:35.660
to questions that
we haven't actually

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:39.370
asked with our studies.

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:41.590
So with that in mind, I
wanted to just reflect

00:16:41.590 --> 00:16:45.070
a little bit on the future of
epidemiology, or at least some

00:16:45.070 --> 00:16:48.970
of the themes that I
really see set out there

00:16:48.970 --> 00:16:52.780
by a lot of my colleagues,
including bigger data, better

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:56.020
data, and then novel uses of
some of the newer kinds of data

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:59.430
that we have access to.

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:01.530
So first in terms of big data.

00:17:01.530 --> 00:17:03.320
We heard a little bit
about the promises

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:05.569
of electronic medical records.

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:07.640
We've thought through
things like registries.

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:09.829
There's a lot of
web-based data out there.

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:13.160
You can use Google searches
to predict flu epidemics.

00:17:13.160 --> 00:17:17.569
You can use Facebook networks
to understand social contagion.

00:17:17.569 --> 00:17:19.170
There's a lot of app-based data.

00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:22.730
So if you're wearing a Fitbit,
we can, in research settings,

00:17:22.730 --> 00:17:28.294
use that information to really
get an idea of your behaviors.

00:17:28.294 --> 00:17:29.960
And then some of the
newer kinds of data

00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:31.860
are big just by definition.

00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:34.130
Genetics and
epigenetics and imaging

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:37.340
collects huge amounts
of data points.

00:17:37.340 --> 00:17:38.950
So this is all really
exciting, and I

00:17:38.950 --> 00:17:41.800
feel thrilled to be an
epidemiologist at an era

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:43.596
when these resources exist.

00:17:43.596 --> 00:17:45.970
But I think we have to be
mindful that the big data alone

00:17:45.970 --> 00:17:47.720
is not why it's exciting.

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:49.210
It's exciting
because we can tie it

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:51.260
to the questions
we're trying to ask,

00:17:51.260 --> 00:17:54.520
and we can find a way to
answer those questions using

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:56.890
this data.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:17:59.170
The same kind of thing could
be said for better data

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:01.090
that I think we're
getting better and better

00:18:01.090 --> 00:18:02.680
about having more
valid measurements,

00:18:02.680 --> 00:18:06.340
having repeated
measurements in individuals,

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:09.130
and then certainly getting
kinds of measurements that

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:11.140
let us peer into
human biology in a way

00:18:11.140 --> 00:18:15.460
that we just weren't
able to decades before.

00:18:15.460 --> 00:18:17.380
As just one example
of this, I work

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:20.170
with a couple of cohort
studies in the Netherlands

00:18:20.170 --> 00:18:22.330
where we have
repeated brain imaging

00:18:22.330 --> 00:18:24.250
on individuals in our studies.

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:29.410
So across childhood development
all the way through the elderly

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:32.350
we're able to kind of
see how the brains change

00:18:32.350 --> 00:18:34.510
in these large studies.

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:36.340
And this is really
exciting and it really

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:39.070
opens these opportunities to
understand what healthy aging

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:41.500
looks like, how we can
prevent cognitive decline,

00:18:41.500 --> 00:18:44.830
how we could promote
better brain development

00:18:44.830 --> 00:18:46.960
during childhood, and so on.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:48.700
But it's exciting
because we can tie

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:52.530
that data to these questions.

00:18:52.530 --> 00:18:54.360
And then finally,
some of the newer data

00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:58.080
allows us to have new
uses for this data.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:00.630
And one example that's similar
to the quasi-experimental

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:02.190
designs we heard
about earlier is

00:19:02.190 --> 00:19:03.960
this idea that
our genes could be

00:19:03.960 --> 00:19:06.409
leveraged as a
natural experiment.

00:19:06.409 --> 00:19:08.700
That, for example, if you
started with a question about

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.280
whether obesity affects
mental health outcomes,

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:14.310
you could look at
obesity-related genes

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:17.080
as a proxy for leveraging
this natural experiment

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:20.272
to try to answer that question.

00:19:20.272 --> 00:19:21.730
And, again, that's
really exciting,

00:19:21.730 --> 00:19:24.250
but these advanced
methods as well as

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:25.720
the bigger data
and the better data

00:19:25.720 --> 00:19:27.760
alone are not going
to save us from having

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:29.050
imprecise questions.

00:19:29.050 --> 00:19:30.490
That we need to
think through how

00:19:30.490 --> 00:19:33.340
we're using this to get
back to those big questions,

00:19:33.340 --> 00:19:35.830
back to the more precise
versions of them,

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:37.150
and really tie it all together.

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:43.090
And so what is the
future of epidemiology?

00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:45.040
Well, when I think
about these big themes,

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:48.710
I think about them all as
fitting into this whole process

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:49.969
that I was going through.

00:19:49.969 --> 00:19:51.760
That we're starting
with this big question.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:53.950
We're distilling it down
to these more manageable

00:19:53.950 --> 00:19:57.220
questions, collecting
and analyzing data,

00:19:57.220 --> 00:19:59.620
and discussing the
results transparently.

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:02.350
And so these are offering
us huge opportunities

00:20:02.350 --> 00:20:04.294
to kind of get at
this middle step,

00:20:04.294 --> 00:20:05.710
but we need to be
mindful of where

00:20:05.710 --> 00:20:08.030
it fits in the whole process.

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:10.300
So finally, I just wanted
to talk a little bit

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:13.360
about one of the key roles
of epidemiologists here,

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:16.520
which is being communicators
about all of this.

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:19.990
So part of the themes of what I
just went through highlight how

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:22.780
we communicate our results
to fellow epidemiologists

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:24.820
and fellow scientists,
but we also

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:26.980
have to be mindful
that this conversation

00:20:26.980 --> 00:20:29.440
is much bigger than just
the scientific community.

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:33.850
We want our research to
be informing policies

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:35.140
at some level.

00:20:35.140 --> 00:20:37.600
We want health care providers,
patients in communities,

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:41.200
to understand the
impact of these findings

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:44.546
and use that to inform
their decisions.

00:20:44.546 --> 00:20:46.420
And ultimately, I see
that this communication

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:50.140
is improved by specifically
tie into questions

00:20:50.140 --> 00:20:52.930
that we want to answer to the
way that we answer to them.

00:20:52.930 --> 00:20:54.490
So the way we
collect and use data

00:20:54.490 --> 00:20:57.670
to answer them as directly
and best as we can

00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:00.117
and keep that process going.

00:21:00.117 --> 00:21:01.700
And so with that, I
just want to thank

00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:05.060
the numerous collaborators that
have shaped many of the ideas

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:07.262
that I went through
here, and thank you

00:21:07.262 --> 00:21:08.220
all for your attention.

00:21:08.220 --> 00:21:10.710
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:15.700 --> 00:21:20.230
- So I would like to thank all
of my co-presenters for just

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:24.930
beautifully setting up my talk.

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:28.220
No, I really want to
give you guys a big hug.

00:21:28.220 --> 00:21:29.030
Let me know--

00:21:29.030 --> 00:21:29.530
OK.

00:21:29.530 --> 00:21:30.250
There we go.

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:33.420
So most of my work is--

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:37.300
I'm really interested in how
we as epidemiologists can

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.480
use data to make
progress in actually

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:42.770
reducing health disparities.

00:21:42.770 --> 00:21:45.717
So I just started at
Johns Hopkins, and lo

00:21:45.717 --> 00:21:47.800
and behold I found out
that a lot of my colleagues

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:50.320
are actually developing
and evaluating

00:21:50.320 --> 00:21:52.990
interventions to reduce
disparities in health.

00:21:52.990 --> 00:21:56.260
So, for example, reducing
differences in hypertension

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:58.610
control between
blacks and whites.

00:21:58.610 --> 00:22:00.190
And a lot of these
interventions are

00:22:00.190 --> 00:22:02.290
based on our current
understanding

00:22:02.290 --> 00:22:04.600
of the epidemiology
and about logic models,

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:07.120
and so I'm wondering about
the sorts of questions

00:22:07.120 --> 00:22:09.580
that we're asking
when we're informing

00:22:09.580 --> 00:22:12.290
those sorts of interventions,
and what those interventions

00:22:12.290 --> 00:22:13.420
should target.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:15.878
So that's really what I'm going
to talk to you about today.

00:22:15.878 --> 00:22:17.750
In my mind, I think
of it as a work

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:20.930
that's helping to
extend and further build

00:22:20.930 --> 00:22:24.450
an epidemiology of
health disparities.

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:25.870
So before I begin,
I think there's

00:22:25.870 --> 00:22:29.140
some background material
that needs to be covered.

00:22:29.140 --> 00:22:31.360
And what do I mean by
a health disparity?

00:22:31.360 --> 00:22:36.010
It's not just a difference
in diseases across groups.

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:38.740
The one definition that
really resonates with me

00:22:38.740 --> 00:22:41.590
is one that was put forth
by Margaret Whitehead

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:43.690
for the World
Health Organization,

00:22:43.690 --> 00:22:45.640
later updated by
Paula Braveman that

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:49.420
says that it's a disparity
in outcomes across socially

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:51.940
defined groups that results
through some mechanism

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:57.430
of injustice or a process
of marginalization.

00:22:57.430 --> 00:23:01.080
So, for example, in the United
States racial ethnic minorities

00:23:01.080 --> 00:23:04.540
because of the history
of Jim Crow, slavery,

00:23:04.540 --> 00:23:07.210
structural racism,
segregation, housing

00:23:07.210 --> 00:23:10.780
policy, interpersonal
discrimination, and also

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:15.220
lately implicit bias,
this has erected

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:18.880
significant political and
economic barriers which have,

00:23:18.880 --> 00:23:22.300
number one, predisposed
racial ethnic minorities

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:26.560
to a higher likelihood
of being exposed

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:28.420
to environmental
toxins, psychological

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:31.630
stresses, impeded their
ability to lead and engage

00:23:31.630 --> 00:23:36.010
in healthier lifestyles,
and also erected barriers

00:23:36.010 --> 00:23:40.000
to quality care.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.130
Just to make things a
little bit more concrete

00:23:42.130 --> 00:23:45.850
about incorporating
this notion of justice

00:23:45.850 --> 00:23:49.540
into our measurement
of other disparities,

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:51.490
it's actually useful
to look at the way

00:23:51.490 --> 00:23:54.490
the Institute of Medicine
defines a disparity

00:23:54.490 --> 00:23:56.320
in the receipt of health care.

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:00.940
They would define a disparity
in receipt of health care

00:24:00.940 --> 00:24:04.060
that should capture differences
that arise in access to care,

00:24:04.060 --> 00:24:06.390
or differences that arise
in the ability to pay,

00:24:06.390 --> 00:24:09.190
or differences that arise
because perhaps the clinician

00:24:09.190 --> 00:24:10.960
in the face of
clinical uncertainty

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:14.530
is relying on poor
provider-patient communication,

00:24:14.530 --> 00:24:17.530
or perhaps
stereotypes associated

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:20.350
with the social group
that a patient belongs to.

00:24:20.350 --> 00:24:22.780
But if there were
actual differences

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:25.840
in the clinical need
between the populations

00:24:25.840 --> 00:24:27.814
and there were differences
because of that,

00:24:27.814 --> 00:24:30.230
that's not something that would
contribute to a disparity.

00:24:30.230 --> 00:24:34.450
So, for example, in the
same psychiatric studies

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:36.550
that Sonya was
talking about, you

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:41.770
see a 60% lower prevalence of
major depression for blacks.

00:24:41.770 --> 00:24:45.460
And so if you see
disparities in treatment

00:24:45.460 --> 00:24:47.860
that may not necessarily
constitute a disparity.

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:50.470
You would want to estimate
disparities in anti-depressant

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:52.660
use among those who
have a clinical need

00:24:52.660 --> 00:24:54.460
for antidepressants.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:57.250
So it's clear that our
measures of disparity

00:24:57.250 --> 00:25:00.890
should be capturing processes
that involve marginalization

00:25:00.890 --> 00:25:02.350
and also injustice.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:04.150
So in thinking of the health--

00:25:04.150 --> 00:25:07.630
of the epidemiology
of health disparities,

00:25:07.630 --> 00:25:09.880
I think it's also good
to go back to the basics.

00:25:09.880 --> 00:25:12.460
Even though this has
been a central theme

00:25:12.460 --> 00:25:15.130
throughout the day,
we're essentially

00:25:15.130 --> 00:25:18.640
charged with understanding
how diseases are

00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:21.370
distributed in the population.

00:25:21.370 --> 00:25:23.680
And one of the major
hallmarks of epidemiology

00:25:23.680 --> 00:25:26.710
has been to identify what
are the causal factors that

00:25:26.710 --> 00:25:31.150
are actually influencing
disease with the ultimate goal

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:35.870
that we develop interventions
to improve population health.

00:25:35.870 --> 00:25:39.070
This is a conceptual model by
the late Brian MacMahon, who

00:25:39.070 --> 00:25:42.010
first chaired the
Department of Epidemiology

00:25:42.010 --> 00:25:45.276
at the Harvard T.H Chan
School of Public Health.

00:25:45.276 --> 00:25:51.520
And what-- and in
this model it reflects

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:55.686
the current thinking at the
time where chronic diseases--

00:25:55.686 --> 00:25:58.060
it was realized that chronic
diseases weren't just caused

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:01.750
by a single agent but actually
a constellation of factors.

00:26:01.750 --> 00:26:04.120
And a key insight of
his was that it's not

00:26:04.120 --> 00:26:07.750
necessary to map out the entire
causal structure of a disease

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:13.450
or how all of these factors
coordinate and orchestrate

00:26:13.450 --> 00:26:14.690
to cause disease.

00:26:14.690 --> 00:26:17.830
But rather, it's important
to identify the particularly

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:20.440
salient causes that
intervening on them,

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:26.030
we could reduce a substantial
amount of disease and morbidity

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:28.220
in the population.

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:29.950
Now this aspect
of multi-causation

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:32.460
has been discussed
quite a bit today.

00:26:32.460 --> 00:26:35.200
It's been a thorn in the
side of many epidemiologists,

00:26:35.200 --> 00:26:39.750
because these causes are
correlated with each other.

00:26:39.750 --> 00:26:42.190
And so in the absence
of a randomized trial--

00:26:42.190 --> 00:26:45.760
say, if I was going to look
at the effect of eating

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:50.240
a healthier diet and whether I
could control my hypertension--

00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:53.680
well, it might be that
patients like me also

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:56.680
live in neighborhoods
that are food deserts

00:26:56.680 --> 00:27:00.070
and don't have opportunities
to buy healthier foods,

00:27:00.070 --> 00:27:03.820
but the streets also may
not be safe to exercise on.

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:07.720
There may not be facilities
where I can go and exercise.

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:09.880
So you have this
correlation between being

00:27:09.880 --> 00:27:15.650
able to eat a nutritious meal
and also exercise regularly.

00:27:15.650 --> 00:27:19.550
And so without going into it,
we've heard about this today,

00:27:19.550 --> 00:27:22.240
but I spent the last five
to eight years of my life

00:27:22.240 --> 00:27:27.010
learning how to tease out this
association between causes

00:27:27.010 --> 00:27:29.710
to try to map towards
a randomized trial.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:32.710
Some of that involves tools
like propensity score matching,

00:27:32.710 --> 00:27:37.410
regression discontinuity,
statistical adjustment.

00:27:37.410 --> 00:27:41.460
This is a figure showing the
life expectancy in the United

00:27:41.460 --> 00:27:48.270
States from 1975 to 2003 for
blacks and whites segregated

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:50.460
by sex.

00:27:50.460 --> 00:27:53.580
What you see here is you
see that for all groups

00:27:53.580 --> 00:27:57.150
you see an improvement in life
expectancy by at least six

00:27:57.150 --> 00:28:02.220
to eight years, but you also
see that the racial difference

00:28:02.220 --> 00:28:05.280
in life expectancy
over that period

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:07.925
has persisted for both
males and females.

00:28:07.925 --> 00:28:12.030
And so the implication
of this figure to me

00:28:12.030 --> 00:28:15.990
is that simply understanding
and intervening

00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:19.290
on the determinants of health
or determinants of disease

00:28:19.290 --> 00:28:21.900
may improve population health,
but it may not necessarily

00:28:21.900 --> 00:28:27.310
translate into the
reduction of disparities.

00:28:27.310 --> 00:28:31.260
One of the major thinkers
of health disparities

00:28:31.260 --> 00:28:33.210
and their genesis
is Sherman James.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:37.890
He was the pioneer of
studying health disparities.

00:28:37.890 --> 00:28:42.450
And what-- in this model
what I particularly like

00:28:42.450 --> 00:28:45.330
is that he's linking a
determinant of disease

00:28:45.330 --> 00:28:47.520
to disparities and
outcomes, and he's

00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:49.490
shown this in a very
comprehensive way.

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:54.890
So you see determinants
[INAUDIBLE] disease organized

00:28:54.890 --> 00:28:59.807
as environmental factors also as
behavioral factors, the issues

00:28:59.807 --> 00:29:00.890
of quality in health care.

00:29:00.890 --> 00:29:04.080
Now in the text, you can't
really see this in the figure,

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:06.000
but in the text what
he goes on to say

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:09.090
is that actually the disparities
and these determinants

00:29:09.090 --> 00:29:12.790
of the outcome that are driving
disparities in these outcomes.

00:29:12.790 --> 00:29:15.610
So, for example,
disparities in incidence,

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:18.640
he's arguing, as you can see
by the weight of this arrow,

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:22.440
are driven largely
by disparities

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:24.720
in the environment and
air and housing quality

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:29.040
and in social relationships,
experiencing discrimination,

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:33.150
living in areas where there's
high concentrations of poverty.

00:29:33.150 --> 00:29:34.770
Disparities in
prognosis, though,

00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:36.720
are driven more by
disparities in the access

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:39.670
to and the utilization
of health care

00:29:39.670 --> 00:29:42.810
whereas disparities in mortality
are driven more by prognosis

00:29:42.810 --> 00:29:47.940
and also disparities in
care, with the acknowledgment

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:50.250
that all of these disparities
and these causal factors

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:55.410
are shaped by a larger political
and economic structures.

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:59.095
Now in thinking of
designing an intervention,

00:29:59.095 --> 00:30:00.720
if we had a particular
outcome in mind,

00:30:00.720 --> 00:30:05.350
well, we could target so many
different disparities here.

00:30:05.350 --> 00:30:08.010
So how do we actually choose?

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:09.570
How do we do that?

00:30:09.570 --> 00:30:13.440
And there are numerous
things that we

00:30:13.440 --> 00:30:15.900
have to consider and trade off.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:18.180
For example, how
much will it cost?

00:30:18.180 --> 00:30:19.110
Is it feasible?

00:30:19.110 --> 00:30:21.600
Do we have a window
of opportunity?

00:30:21.600 --> 00:30:23.250
Do we have the political will?

00:30:23.250 --> 00:30:25.470
Do we think that these
interventions are sustainable?

00:30:25.470 --> 00:30:27.930
But I think the key
ingredient to all of this

00:30:27.930 --> 00:30:31.170
is solid evidence
that intervening

00:30:31.170 --> 00:30:34.470
to remove disparities
in a particular target

00:30:34.470 --> 00:30:37.590
that we're pretty confident
that it will result in reducing

00:30:37.590 --> 00:30:38.990
disparities in the outcomes.

00:30:38.990 --> 00:30:42.390
So I would call
that effectiveness.

00:30:42.390 --> 00:30:46.260
So how do we actually
use data to understand

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:48.500
how removing
disparities in a target

00:30:48.500 --> 00:30:51.570
will actually lead to a
reduction in disparities

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:52.800
of outcomes?

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:55.140
Without going into the
specifics of this today,

00:30:55.140 --> 00:30:58.020
I would say that most
of what we do today

00:30:58.020 --> 00:31:01.530
is to quantify how disparities
in a particular target

00:31:01.530 --> 00:31:05.400
statistically explain
disparities and outcomes.

00:31:05.400 --> 00:31:08.010
The problem is is that
most of these approaches

00:31:08.010 --> 00:31:12.120
are not explicitly accounting
for potential confounding

00:31:12.120 --> 00:31:14.070
factors of those targets.

00:31:14.070 --> 00:31:17.010
And so we're not ruling
out alternate explanations

00:31:17.010 --> 00:31:20.320
of why those disparities
in those targets

00:31:20.320 --> 00:31:23.572
may statistically explain
disparities and outcomes.

00:31:23.572 --> 00:31:25.530
So if you think back to
that graph I showed you

00:31:25.530 --> 00:31:27.810
about diet and nutrition, there
are these other compounding

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:28.309
factors.

00:31:28.309 --> 00:31:32.040
And that's really what I'm
going to talk to you about today

00:31:32.040 --> 00:31:34.950
is how we can improve these
methods to incorporate

00:31:34.950 --> 00:31:37.740
explicit assumptions
about confounding control.

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:41.460
I'm going to do that by
walking through a very--

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:45.870
what I hope is an easy to
digest example analysis.

00:31:45.870 --> 00:31:51.210
I'm going to re-use data from
a seminal paper by Roland Fryer

00:31:51.210 --> 00:31:54.990
who's actually a renowned
economist here at Harvard

00:31:54.990 --> 00:31:58.170
University, who showed that
if you look at the association

00:31:58.170 --> 00:31:59.890
between race--

00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:02.490
and some key outcomes,
including race, incarceration,

00:32:02.490 --> 00:32:03.900
and unemployment--

00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:06.780
if you adjust for
educational attainment,

00:32:06.780 --> 00:32:10.090
you see that those disparities
reduce substantially.

00:32:10.090 --> 00:32:13.850
And in the case of health, you
see that the disparity actually

00:32:13.850 --> 00:32:15.720
vanishes.

00:32:15.720 --> 00:32:18.560
And so essentially
what the data shows

00:32:18.560 --> 00:32:20.910
is that disparities in
educational attainment or test

00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:25.410
scores statistically explain
disparities in wages,

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:28.570
disparities in incarceration,
and disparities in health.

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:32.160
But there are alternate
explanations we could consider.

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:35.520
For example, it may
be that disparities

00:32:35.520 --> 00:32:37.180
in educational
attainment are merely

00:32:37.180 --> 00:32:39.430
a reflection of
disparities in childhood

00:32:39.430 --> 00:32:41.410
socioeconomic conditions.

00:32:41.410 --> 00:32:45.010
And so it begs the question,
will we see those same results

00:32:45.010 --> 00:32:48.520
if we repeat the analyses to
actually control for childhood

00:32:48.520 --> 00:32:50.380
socioeconomic conditions?

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:55.660
Another question is, well,
maybe the attractive target

00:32:55.660 --> 00:32:57.520
could be test scores,
but maybe the target

00:32:57.520 --> 00:33:00.010
could be to actually remove
disparities in childhood

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:01.750
socioeconomic conditions.

00:33:01.750 --> 00:33:03.610
It's another question
we could ask.

00:33:03.610 --> 00:33:05.320
A third question
is, well, what if we

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:07.150
could remove disparities
in both childhood

00:33:07.150 --> 00:33:10.090
socioeconomic conditions
and test scores?

00:33:10.090 --> 00:33:11.770
And so what I would
like to do is just

00:33:11.770 --> 00:33:18.370
to walk through a couple of
example questions in this data,

00:33:18.370 --> 00:33:23.110
incorporating, again, clear
assumptions about confounding.

00:33:23.110 --> 00:33:26.670
And even though the
methods are going

00:33:26.670 --> 00:33:29.370
to be really pretty
accessible and pretty simple,

00:33:29.370 --> 00:33:32.100
they do draw on a power
counterfactual framework that

00:33:32.100 --> 00:33:34.530
does map to a
hypothetical trial, which

00:33:34.530 --> 00:33:38.520
allows you to really say if you
believe that you've measured

00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:41.550
and adjusted for all the
appropriate confounders

00:33:41.550 --> 00:33:44.250
that you can interpret it
as an intervention effect.

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:47.490
And so really what you're
asking is if we could intervene

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:51.900
to equalize these risk factors,
if we could intervene to remove

00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:55.170
disparities in this target, how
would that impact disparities

00:33:55.170 --> 00:33:56.940
in the outcome?

00:33:56.940 --> 00:34:01.142
And so I'm going to run
through four analyses.

00:34:01.142 --> 00:34:02.600
One, I'm going to
ask, what's going

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:05.570
to happen to the disparities
in wages, incarceration,

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:08.210
and in health if we could
remove disparities in childhood

00:34:08.210 --> 00:34:10.219
socioeconomic conditions?

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:14.799
Then I'm going to ask, what
would happen to disparities

00:34:14.799 --> 00:34:18.440
in our outcomes if among
those with the same childhood

00:34:18.440 --> 00:34:21.860
socioeconomic status, we
could remove disparities

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:24.139
in educational attainment
as reflected in test scores?

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:26.630
And, again, I'm changing
the population here,

00:34:26.630 --> 00:34:29.150
because I want to rule out
differences in childhood

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:30.159
socioeconomic status.

00:34:30.159 --> 00:34:32.179
I'm going to account
for confounding.

00:34:32.179 --> 00:34:34.779
The third one is, what if
we could intervene jointly

00:34:34.779 --> 00:34:37.070
to remove disparities in
childhood socioeconomic status

00:34:37.070 --> 00:34:38.370
and test scores?

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:42.080
And the last one is really, what
if we could remove disparities

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:45.330
overall irrespective of
childhood socioeconomic status,

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:49.820
which may be something that
we're more interested in.

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:52.760
So consider our
first intervention

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:55.610
to remove disparities in
childhood socioeconomic status.

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:57.560
Under some pretty
strong assumptions

00:34:57.560 --> 00:34:59.570
and in this
simplified example, we

00:34:59.570 --> 00:35:01.490
could estimate this
by fitting a model

00:35:01.490 --> 00:35:05.880
for our outcome given race and
the covariate's age, gender,

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:07.460
and ethnicity.

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:09.620
And the race coefficient
in that model

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:11.990
would simply describe
the disparity

00:35:11.990 --> 00:35:14.580
in the population
as we we've observed

00:35:14.580 --> 00:35:17.690
for people the same age,
gender, and ethnicity.

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:20.540
Now if we refit that model and
we include a term for childhood

00:35:20.540 --> 00:35:23.660
socioeconomic conditions, again,
under some strong assumptions

00:35:23.660 --> 00:35:29.060
we would interpret that
as the remaining disparity

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:31.330
in our outcomes
after an intervention

00:35:31.330 --> 00:35:36.170
to remove disparities in
childhood socioeconomic status.

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:38.420
The key assumption
here is that we've

00:35:38.420 --> 00:35:40.940
adjusted for all the
confounders of childhood

00:35:40.940 --> 00:35:43.820
socioeconomic status, and we've
heard a lot about that those

00:35:43.820 --> 00:35:46.760
are usually pre-treatment
variables that

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:49.940
are also determinants
of whatever outcomes

00:35:49.940 --> 00:35:51.240
that you're studying.

00:35:51.240 --> 00:35:55.070
So conceptually, what
does this really mean?

00:35:55.070 --> 00:35:58.240
So to help us sort through
this, I created some figures.

00:35:58.240 --> 00:36:01.370
So on this top line here,
you see the distributions

00:36:01.370 --> 00:36:05.300
of childhood
socioeconomic conditions,

00:36:05.300 --> 00:36:08.225
educational attainment as
measured by test scores,

00:36:08.225 --> 00:36:12.266
and the distributions
of our outcome.

00:36:12.266 --> 00:36:14.765
And on the bottom, we have the
counterfactual distributions.

00:36:14.765 --> 00:36:17.170
And this is for blacks
and then for whites.

00:36:17.170 --> 00:36:19.080
So we have the
counterfactual distributions.

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:21.790
And so what the yellow
arrow represents

00:36:21.790 --> 00:36:24.470
is the effect of
our intervention

00:36:24.470 --> 00:36:27.230
to actively remove
disparities in childhood

00:36:27.230 --> 00:36:28.730
socioeconomic conditions.

00:36:28.730 --> 00:36:31.630
Namely, to shift the
distribution of childhood

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:33.410
socioeconomic conditions
such that they

00:36:33.410 --> 00:36:35.840
align with the
distribution of childhood

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:38.750
socioeconomic
conditions for whites.

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:42.590
The faint dotted arrow
represents the propagation

00:36:42.590 --> 00:36:46.590
of this effect to reduce
disparities in test scores

00:36:46.590 --> 00:36:50.390
and also reduce disparities
in our outcomes finally.

00:36:50.390 --> 00:36:52.310
So that was our
first intervention

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:53.790
to remove disparities
in childhood

00:36:53.790 --> 00:36:56.390
socioeconomic conditions.

00:36:56.390 --> 00:36:59.600
Our second intervention
is to remove disparities

00:36:59.600 --> 00:37:03.230
in our outcomes among
those of the same childhood

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:07.790
socioeconomic conditions
and by removing disparities

00:37:07.790 --> 00:37:12.020
in educational attainment
as reflected in test scores.

00:37:12.020 --> 00:37:14.360
So, again, under some
pretty strong assumptions,

00:37:14.360 --> 00:37:18.470
we could estimate this by
fitting a model for our outcome

00:37:18.470 --> 00:37:21.172
given race on the covariate's
age, gender, and ethnicity,

00:37:21.172 --> 00:37:23.630
but we also want to include in
this initial model childhood

00:37:23.630 --> 00:37:25.422
socioeconomic conditions,
because we want

00:37:25.422 --> 00:37:27.110
to account for confounding.

00:37:27.110 --> 00:37:29.780
So, again, now the race
coefficient in that model

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:32.390
is going to give us our
observed disparity among people

00:37:32.390 --> 00:37:37.820
who share the same socioeconomic
status in childhood.

00:37:37.820 --> 00:37:41.440
Now we're going to add to that
model a term for test scores.

00:37:41.440 --> 00:37:43.820
And what this and
the race coefficient

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:46.520
in this new model would equal--

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:49.130
again, under some
strong assumptions--

00:37:49.130 --> 00:37:53.000
what the disparity we would
observe after an intervention

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:57.170
to remove disparities
in test scores

00:37:57.170 --> 00:38:00.740
among those who have the same
childhood socioeconomic status.

00:38:00.740 --> 00:38:02.240
Again, this is
under an assumption

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:05.564
that we've measured all the
confounders of test scores

00:38:05.564 --> 00:38:06.480
and adjusted for them.

00:38:06.480 --> 00:38:11.420
So heuristically what's
going on here is we're--

00:38:11.420 --> 00:38:13.580
I'm showing you the
distributions of childhood

00:38:13.580 --> 00:38:16.520
socioeconomic
conditions, and then I'm

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:20.300
showing you the black and white
distributions for test scores

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:22.250
among those with low
socioeconomic status

00:38:22.250 --> 00:38:24.500
and among those with high
socioeconomic status,

00:38:24.500 --> 00:38:26.240
and then also for the outcomes.

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:30.850
Again, conditional on
childhood socioeconomic status.

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:35.280
And on the bottom line, we have
our counterfactual disparities.

00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:38.000
So the intervention doesn't
touch socioeconomic status

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:41.390
at all, but rather
it's within levels

00:38:41.390 --> 00:38:43.490
or among those who
share the same childhood

00:38:43.490 --> 00:38:44.580
socioeconomic status.

00:38:44.580 --> 00:38:47.279
So there are some details
I put into this figure

00:38:47.279 --> 00:38:48.320
that I want to point out.

00:38:48.320 --> 00:38:51.440
The first detail is that for
those with lower childhood

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:54.170
socioeconomic status,
it's highly plausible

00:38:54.170 --> 00:38:56.430
that the distribution of
test scores for both blacks

00:38:56.430 --> 00:39:00.930
and whites is actually lower
than the population average.

00:39:00.930 --> 00:39:04.470
And then, again, for those with
high childhood socioeconomic

00:39:04.470 --> 00:39:07.140
conditions, their distributions
are going to be higher.

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:10.200
The implication of this is that
when we do our intervention

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:14.010
to shift the black distribution
to where the white distribution

00:39:14.010 --> 00:39:16.140
is, for those with low
socioeconomic status

00:39:16.140 --> 00:39:18.030
we're not going to
move it that far.

00:39:18.030 --> 00:39:20.400
But this is problematic,
because this is where

00:39:20.400 --> 00:39:22.440
blacks are overrepresented.

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:25.620
And so our intervention
to reduce disparities

00:39:25.620 --> 00:39:28.440
in educational attainment among
those with the same childhood

00:39:28.440 --> 00:39:30.810
socioeconomic status
is probably not

00:39:30.810 --> 00:39:34.020
going to achieve as much
as we would like it to.

00:39:34.020 --> 00:39:35.730
But yet this is
the very analysis,

00:39:35.730 --> 00:39:38.070
this is the principal
analysis that we have to do,

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:41.280
because we want to
count for confounding.

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:43.110
My childhood
socioeconomic status.

00:39:43.110 --> 00:39:45.300
So our third
intervention is to look

00:39:45.300 --> 00:39:48.810
at what could happen if we could
intervene to reduce disparities

00:39:48.810 --> 00:39:53.730
in both childhood socioeconomic
conditions and also

00:39:53.730 --> 00:39:56.410
educational attainment as
reflected in test scores.

00:39:56.410 --> 00:39:58.200
So as similar to
before, we're going

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:00.300
to start with a model
for outcome given race

00:40:00.300 --> 00:40:02.400
and the covariate's initial.

00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:04.170
Race coefficient
is the disparity

00:40:04.170 --> 00:40:05.970
we observe in the population.

00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:10.650
If we add in terms for childhood
socioeconomic status and also

00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:13.740
test scores, the
new race coefficient

00:40:13.740 --> 00:40:17.070
is going to-- we could interpret
that as the residual disparity

00:40:17.070 --> 00:40:19.680
we would see under an
intervention to jointly remove

00:40:19.680 --> 00:40:22.620
disparities in childhood
socioeconomic status

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:24.130
and also test scores.

00:40:24.130 --> 00:40:26.130
Here, we have a stronger
confounding assumptions

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:27.360
that we need to meet.

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:30.360
We need to ensure that there
is no unmeasured confounding

00:40:30.360 --> 00:40:32.820
for childhood socioeconomic
status, and also

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:35.410
no unmeasured confounding
for test scores.

00:40:35.410 --> 00:40:39.090
So this is a stronger
assumption that we need than we

00:40:39.090 --> 00:40:42.350
used for our other analyses.

00:40:42.350 --> 00:40:45.810
And so heuristically, these
are observed distributions

00:40:45.810 --> 00:40:48.330
for childhood socioeconomic
status test scores and outcome,

00:40:48.330 --> 00:40:49.788
and you can see
our intervention is

00:40:49.788 --> 00:40:54.120
to shift the distributions of
childhood socioeconomic status

00:40:54.120 --> 00:40:58.800
and test scores for blacks to
their respective distributions

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:02.400
among whites and observe some
reduction in the disparity

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:03.600
in the outcomes.

00:41:03.600 --> 00:41:06.390
So I've described to you
so far three interventions.

00:41:06.390 --> 00:41:09.660
The first intervention would
be to reduce disparities

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:11.886
in childhood
socioeconomic status.

00:41:11.886 --> 00:41:13.260
The second one is
where we wanted

00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:16.380
to look at the impact
of removing disparities

00:41:16.380 --> 00:41:18.180
in test scores,
but we had to do it

00:41:18.180 --> 00:41:21.157
among a special group of people
who share the same childhood

00:41:21.157 --> 00:41:22.740
socioeconomic status
because we wanted

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:24.630
to control for confounding.

00:41:24.630 --> 00:41:26.190
And this third one
was we said, well,

00:41:26.190 --> 00:41:28.530
let's just try to
intervene on both.

00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:30.960
But really an intervention
that we might think about

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:34.320
is, well, what if we could just
move disparities in test scores

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:37.590
without even
looking at childhood

00:41:37.590 --> 00:41:41.200
socioeconomic conditions but
account for the confounding

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:41.700
there?

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:43.680
That's the real trick.

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:45.642
That's the real tough one there.

00:41:45.642 --> 00:41:47.100
And we're interested
in doing this,

00:41:47.100 --> 00:41:49.590
because it may be more
feasible to remove disparities

00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:52.140
in educational attainment
than to remove disparities

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:55.030
in economic conditions.

00:41:55.030 --> 00:41:57.180
So without getting into
too much of the math,

00:41:57.180 --> 00:42:00.330
it turns out to
estimate this, to answer

00:42:00.330 --> 00:42:04.200
this sort of question, we can't
rely on the typical subtraction

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:06.120
of race coefficients.

00:42:06.120 --> 00:42:10.500
And the reason why is that
an intervention to remove

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:12.690
disparities in
test scores overall

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:15.840
is going to partially block
the effects of disparities

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:18.660
in childhood
socioeconomic conditions.

00:42:18.660 --> 00:42:22.500
And so without-- so if we
think of it another way,

00:42:22.500 --> 00:42:24.510
the effect of childhood
socioeconomic status

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:28.000
on our outcomes is partially
mediated by test scores.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:30.210
So if we intervene,
we're going to block

00:42:30.210 --> 00:42:32.220
part of the effect of
disparities in childhood

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:34.560
socioeconomic conditions.

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:38.310
And in English the way
that this is estimated

00:42:38.310 --> 00:42:42.570
in these linear models
is simply to first start

00:42:42.570 --> 00:42:48.090
with the disparity reduction
upon equalizing test scores

00:42:48.090 --> 00:42:50.490
among those with the same
childhood socioeconomic status.

00:42:50.490 --> 00:42:52.290
That was our second
intervention.

00:42:52.290 --> 00:42:54.930
Then we're going to add to that
how much the disparity would

00:42:54.930 --> 00:42:57.490
be reduced under removing
disparities in childhood

00:42:57.490 --> 00:42:58.710
socioeconomic status.

00:42:58.710 --> 00:43:00.390
That was our first intervention.

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:02.460
But we're not going to
add all of that back in.

00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:05.010
We're only going to
add in the amount

00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:09.000
by which the effect of childhood
socioeconomic status is not--

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:13.650
well, is mediated
by test scores.

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:16.590
And so heuristically
all we're doing here

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.206
is intervening to shift the
entire distribution of test

00:43:19.206 --> 00:43:20.830
scores among blacks
to where whites is,

00:43:20.830 --> 00:43:24.050
but we're not doing anything to
the distribution of childhood

00:43:24.050 --> 00:43:25.960
socioeconomic conditions.

00:43:25.960 --> 00:43:30.180
So in our re-analysis of
the data, what do we see?

00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:33.270
Well, we see as we would
expect that the most effective

00:43:33.270 --> 00:43:39.930
intervention is to remove
disparities in both childhood

00:43:39.930 --> 00:43:42.590
socioeconomic conditions
and also test scores.

00:43:42.590 --> 00:43:46.710
So it would removed 74% of
the disparities in wages,

00:43:46.710 --> 00:43:48.900
81% of disparities
in incarceration,

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:54.000
and completely eliminates all
the disparities in health.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:57.030
What's fascinating,
though, is that if we just

00:43:57.030 --> 00:44:00.210
were to remove disparities in
educational attainment alone

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:02.760
as measured in test scores,
it's not that far behind.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:06.090
We could remove two
thirds of the disparities

00:44:06.090 --> 00:44:09.930
in wages, two thirds of the
disparities in incarceration,

00:44:09.930 --> 00:44:12.720
and once you account
for the standard errors,

00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:14.550
all of the disparity in health.

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:17.580
What's also interesting
is that it's

00:44:17.580 --> 00:44:20.490
as effective or more
effective than intervening

00:44:20.490 --> 00:44:22.350
to reduce disparities
in childhood

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:24.120
socioeconomic conditions.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.550
And so just looking at
wage-- disparities in wages

00:44:26.550 --> 00:44:29.430
here, if we removed
disparities in childhood

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:31.650
socioeconomic conditions
we remove about a quarter

00:44:31.650 --> 00:44:32.880
of the disparity.

00:44:32.880 --> 00:44:35.910
But if we were to intervene
to remove disparities

00:44:35.910 --> 00:44:39.420
in educational attainment
as reflected in test scores,

00:44:39.420 --> 00:44:43.350
we would remove two
thirds of the disparity.

00:44:43.350 --> 00:44:47.370
And finally, our--
and eventually we're

00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:49.495
going to remove disparities
among those who have

00:44:49.495 --> 00:44:51.260
the same socioeconomic status.

00:44:51.260 --> 00:44:53.960
Remove 65% of the
disparity among those

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:56.910
who have the same socioeconomic
status, but it bears pointing

00:44:56.910 --> 00:45:01.290
out that this is a
less ambitious goal

00:45:01.290 --> 00:45:03.815
because the initial
disparity is smaller.

00:45:03.815 --> 00:45:06.380
And so if you just
look at that--

00:45:06.380 --> 00:45:09.270
the difference between where
you start and where you end up,

00:45:09.270 --> 00:45:14.510
you can see that it's a
less effective intervention.

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:18.560
Also, the nature of what we
mean by educational attainment

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:22.130
is important, which gets back
to Sonja's point about what

00:45:22.130 --> 00:45:23.210
question are we asking.

00:45:23.210 --> 00:45:26.320
If we were to try to equalize
total years of education,

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:29.720
we see that the
disparity is actually

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:33.320
as effective as equalizing
childhood socioeconomic status,

00:45:33.320 --> 00:45:37.020
or in some cases less effective.

00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:40.650
So there are some limitations.

00:45:40.650 --> 00:45:43.930
We used really simple models and
worked with Tyler VanderWeele,

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.360
which this is based on.

00:45:45.360 --> 00:45:48.200
We've extended these to
more general outcomes,

00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:49.730
non-linear outcomes.

00:45:49.730 --> 00:45:51.290
We have non-parametric
formulae that

00:45:51.290 --> 00:45:54.350
can incorporate interactions,
account for confounders that

00:45:54.350 --> 00:45:57.380
are descendants of race
or whatever social status

00:45:57.380 --> 00:45:58.760
that you're using.

00:45:58.760 --> 00:46:01.970
In future work, we hope
to extend these out

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:04.520
to longitudinal outcomes,
including repeated measures

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:08.090
and time to event outcomes.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:11.690
And also in other work,
it's of great interest today

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:14.720
you hear a lot of people
talking about intersectionality.

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:16.940
So people are not just
marginalized in one way.

00:46:16.940 --> 00:46:19.880
They may be marginalized because
of their socioeconomic position

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:21.170
and also their race.

00:46:21.170 --> 00:46:23.390
In other work, I've
talked about the notion

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:26.420
of joint disparities and also
intersectional disparities,

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:30.380
and it is definitely possible
to map these sorts of analyses

00:46:30.380 --> 00:46:34.760
to disparities
along multiple axes.

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:37.490
The implications of our study,
though-- what we found is we

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:39.260
actually confirmed
the results of Fryer,

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:40.850
but we've added
important information.

00:46:40.850 --> 00:46:43.970
Number one, we've
ruled out disparities

00:46:43.970 --> 00:46:45.620
in childhood
socioeconomic status

00:46:45.620 --> 00:46:46.880
as an alternate explanation.

00:46:46.880 --> 00:46:48.920
It really does look
like disparities

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:52.130
in educational attainment
as reflected in test scores

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:55.580
is really the
important target here.

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:02.840
So what are the implications
for the next steps

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:04.890
in health disparities research?

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:08.280
And I think Sonya
stole my thunder here,

00:47:08.280 --> 00:47:13.620
but what I would like to say is
that we have a real opportunity

00:47:13.620 --> 00:47:16.680
here to do these sorts of
analyses very carefully.

00:47:16.680 --> 00:47:20.310
This was a toy example
here, but when we actually

00:47:20.310 --> 00:47:23.280
have cohort data or
exquisite medical records,

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:25.500
we can actually look at
what is the thing that we're

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:27.834
trying to intervene to
reduce disparities in.

00:47:27.834 --> 00:47:29.750
For example, if we're
looking at it adherence,

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:31.650
or if we're looking
at nutrition,

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:34.650
or if we're looking
at whatever target

00:47:34.650 --> 00:47:36.750
that we're interested
in, we should

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:39.600
think about what are the
confounders of that target.

00:47:39.600 --> 00:47:41.400
And then we should
also try to ensure

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:42.777
that we have longitudinal data.

00:47:42.777 --> 00:47:44.610
We should also try to
ensure that we respect

00:47:44.610 --> 00:47:46.860
the temporality
of our confounders

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:48.690
in our targets and
our outcomes, just

00:47:48.690 --> 00:47:52.350
like we do in careful and
rigorous epidemiologic studies.

00:47:52.350 --> 00:47:56.250
We have a real
opportunity to do this.

00:47:56.250 --> 00:47:59.150
Now all this talk
about confounding,

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:01.960
the big elephant in the room
is unmeasured confounding.

00:48:01.960 --> 00:48:05.216
Which our first speaker
eloquently pointed out

00:48:05.216 --> 00:48:06.840
that sometimes you
have these variables

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:09.780
measured, but many times
they're not measured.

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:12.000
But what I would argue
is that epidemiology

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:13.620
of health disparities
is actually

00:48:13.620 --> 00:48:17.655
in a better position than a
de novo study in epidemiology.

00:48:17.655 --> 00:48:22.890
And the reason is is because
usually health disparities

00:48:22.890 --> 00:48:26.110
analyses are built on existing
knowledge about epidemiology.

00:48:26.110 --> 00:48:27.975
So, for example, if
we're just starting out

00:48:27.975 --> 00:48:32.150
where we're trying to identify
how diseases distribute

00:48:32.150 --> 00:48:33.870
in the population,
well, that's the step

00:48:33.870 --> 00:48:36.640
where we're actually describing
disparities in disease.

00:48:36.640 --> 00:48:38.610
When epidemiology is
doing the hard work

00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:41.700
of trying to identify the
causal factors, teasing out

00:48:41.700 --> 00:48:43.560
what are the other
risk factors, are we

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:47.010
doing the best adjustments
for confounding?

00:48:47.010 --> 00:48:50.130
This is really where
the field of disparities

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:52.380
would still be
determining what are

00:48:52.380 --> 00:48:54.660
the disparities in
those determinants that

00:48:54.660 --> 00:48:57.450
are being identified by
those epidemiologic studies.

00:48:57.450 --> 00:49:01.320
When we go onto
designing strategies

00:49:01.320 --> 00:49:03.960
to improve population
health, part of that we're

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:06.180
thinking about, well, how
can we actually reduce

00:49:06.180 --> 00:49:06.960
these disparities?

00:49:06.960 --> 00:49:09.600
But we have all this
knowledge that we've

00:49:09.600 --> 00:49:11.400
gleaned from these
epidemiologic studies.

00:49:11.400 --> 00:49:13.757
So when I would go and
pull these medical records

00:49:13.757 --> 00:49:15.840
and think about what are
the variables that I need

00:49:15.840 --> 00:49:19.560
to adjust for, well,
for disease areas

00:49:19.560 --> 00:49:21.990
like cardiovascular disease,
we know what the major risk

00:49:21.990 --> 00:49:23.040
factors are.

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:25.224
We know what needs
to be adjusted for.

00:49:25.224 --> 00:49:26.890
And even if our cohorts
don't have them,

00:49:26.890 --> 00:49:29.220
it at least gives
us a clear list

00:49:29.220 --> 00:49:31.260
of things that
need to be measured

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:35.810
in whatever cohorts or synthetic
cohorts that we're designing.

00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:39.780
So I'd argue that, yes, the
confounding structures are

00:49:39.780 --> 00:49:41.550
something to be concerned
about, but we're

00:49:41.550 --> 00:49:45.210
in a much better
position when trying

00:49:45.210 --> 00:49:48.420
to do these sorts of analyses
that I'm describing here.

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:52.440
And hopefully these
sorts of robust analyses

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:54.960
are what's going to be used
to build conceptual models

00:49:54.960 --> 00:49:58.620
for designing interventions.

00:49:58.620 --> 00:50:03.000
Another application of the
work that I'm presenting here

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:08.310
is that how we
define a disparity

00:50:08.310 --> 00:50:10.620
matters exquisitely
for its explanation.

00:50:10.620 --> 00:50:15.031
As I said before, a disparity
measure, particularly when

00:50:15.031 --> 00:50:16.530
it comes to treatment
of care, would

00:50:16.530 --> 00:50:19.500
condition on certain things
and not others, right?

00:50:19.500 --> 00:50:23.670
So in the case of disparities
in anti-depressant treatment,

00:50:23.670 --> 00:50:25.950
we would condition
on clinical need.

00:50:25.950 --> 00:50:28.479
If we went on to condition
on access to care,

00:50:28.479 --> 00:50:30.270
we're going to miss
some of the disparities

00:50:30.270 --> 00:50:33.730
among people who aren't
able to access treatment.

00:50:33.730 --> 00:50:35.490
And so what that
means is when we

00:50:35.490 --> 00:50:37.830
have our covariates that
need to be adjusted for,

00:50:37.830 --> 00:50:39.180
we have a choice.

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:41.640
So we can condition on
things like age and family

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:44.545
history and gender
and prognostics score,

00:50:44.545 --> 00:50:46.920
and we can adjust for them
that way through conditioning.

00:50:46.920 --> 00:50:48.420
But for all of the
other things that

00:50:48.420 --> 00:50:51.920
are sort of tied to injustice,
like socioeconomic status,

00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:55.620
health literacy and
insurance, where you live,

00:50:55.620 --> 00:50:57.287
we don't have to
adjust on those things.

00:50:57.287 --> 00:50:59.411
I mean, we don't have to
condition on those things.

00:50:59.411 --> 00:51:01.640
We can adjust for them
without changing our disparity

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:04.740
measure, which is important.

00:51:04.740 --> 00:51:07.220
So really, it's the hope
that with these sorts

00:51:07.220 --> 00:51:10.790
of careful principled
analyses that we can develop

00:51:10.790 --> 00:51:15.770
refined conceptual models that
will help us provide better

00:51:15.770 --> 00:51:17.390
estimates of how
effective it might

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:20.570
be to intervene on
one particular target

00:51:20.570 --> 00:51:22.220
versus another.

00:51:22.220 --> 00:51:26.457
Thank you for listening, and
I welcome your questions.

00:51:26.457 --> 00:51:28.892
