00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.560
that day, or you
can use GPS data--

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:23.230
obviously with everybody's
permission to use it--

00:53:23.230 --> 00:53:28.930
and see was-- were they
walking by a Dunkin' Donuts?

00:53:28.930 --> 00:53:33.300
You can really get down to
a very fine-grained level.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:35.790
I see Burt's got
a question, too.

00:53:35.790 --> 00:53:36.790
Specific to this.

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:38.194
Yeah?

00:53:38.194 --> 00:53:39.130
- Two great talks.

00:53:39.130 --> 00:53:41.470
Thank you very much.

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:46.290
I have a question--
a question for Sonya.

00:53:46.290 --> 00:53:50.850
You say I would
like to basically do

00:53:50.850 --> 00:53:54.030
a trial to study efficacy,
but I can't very often.

00:53:54.030 --> 00:53:59.130
So let's design a study
to mimic then the trial.

00:53:59.130 --> 00:54:03.450
So that is what you want
to do to do a good study.

00:54:03.450 --> 00:54:08.160
And you also say I would like
to refine the question in such

00:54:08.160 --> 00:54:13.830
a way that I have a meaningful
answer to a good question.

00:54:13.830 --> 00:54:17.580
Now very often-- in
the past-- what is it,

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:19.740
five to 10 years--
clinical trials

00:54:19.740 --> 00:54:22.950
are being criticized for
being not relevant in terms

00:54:22.950 --> 00:54:24.390
of the question they address.

00:54:24.390 --> 00:54:28.170
This tension between what you
want from a design viewpoint

00:54:28.170 --> 00:54:29.730
and from a relevance viewpoint.

00:54:29.730 --> 00:54:31.630
Can you discuss that a bit?

00:54:31.630 --> 00:54:32.650
- Sure.

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:34.830
So I'll just take
one of the criticisms

00:54:34.830 --> 00:54:37.620
I know for trials,
which is that they often

00:54:37.620 --> 00:54:41.640
are focused on really
select patient populations.

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:45.190
So just to stick with the
eating disorder example--

00:54:45.190 --> 00:54:48.420
if you want them to meet exactly
the criteria for anorexia

00:54:48.420 --> 00:54:51.660
nervosa, and you want to rule
out co-morbidities and things

00:54:51.660 --> 00:54:54.180
like that, you might
really restrict the ages.

00:54:54.180 --> 00:54:57.290
You might really restrict
it to females and so on.

00:54:57.290 --> 00:54:59.250
And so you might get
a really good estimate

00:54:59.250 --> 00:55:01.080
in that population
in that trial,

00:55:01.080 --> 00:55:04.870
but it doesn't generalize
to larger populations.

00:55:04.870 --> 00:55:07.260
What I would argue is actually
in observational studies,

00:55:07.260 --> 00:55:10.770
you have this opportunity to
make it exactly the population

00:55:10.770 --> 00:55:11.530
you care about.

00:55:11.530 --> 00:55:14.100
So like when we have
electronic medical records

00:55:14.100 --> 00:55:17.040
or we have big data
opportunities, if we think

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:20.010
about the population we want
to ask the question for,

00:55:20.010 --> 00:55:23.110
we can make it more relevant
and tie it to that population.

00:55:23.110 --> 00:55:26.409
So I see it sort of
as maybe not the trial

00:55:26.409 --> 00:55:28.200
that we would have
conducted, but the trial

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:30.090
we really wish we
could have conducted

00:55:30.090 --> 00:55:31.774
is what you're
trying to emulate.

00:55:31.774 --> 00:55:32.274
Yeah.

00:55:35.650 --> 00:55:37.900
- I've got a question for John.

00:55:37.900 --> 00:55:44.380
This is in the fantasy
baseball camp kind of realm.

00:55:44.380 --> 00:55:47.510
You talked about those
unmeasured confounders,

00:55:47.510 --> 00:55:49.090
and I think very
often when we're

00:55:49.090 --> 00:55:52.900
talking about social
disparities there's

00:55:52.900 --> 00:55:55.420
a lot of elephants
in the room and a lot

00:55:55.420 --> 00:55:57.910
of unmeasured confounders.

00:55:57.910 --> 00:56:02.450
And I think my question
for you would be, you had--

00:56:02.450 --> 00:56:05.240
for that analysis you had the
National Longitudinal Survey

00:56:05.240 --> 00:56:10.220
of Youth, which is actually
a pretty detailed data set.

00:56:10.220 --> 00:56:13.704
What would you ideally want
to answer the question-- first

00:56:13.704 --> 00:56:15.620
of all, what are the
particular questions that

00:56:15.620 --> 00:56:17.570
are most pressing to you?

00:56:17.570 --> 00:56:22.010
And then to get at those, what
are some of the pieces of data

00:56:22.010 --> 00:56:24.490
you'd really love to have?

00:56:24.490 --> 00:56:26.190
- Well, I think--

00:56:26.190 --> 00:56:28.690
so one area that I'm
actually starting to work in

00:56:28.690 --> 00:56:31.660
is in hypertension control.

00:56:31.660 --> 00:56:36.610
So I'm really interested
in lifestyle behaviors

00:56:36.610 --> 00:56:43.360
versus disparities in adherence.

00:56:43.360 --> 00:56:48.010
I think what I tried to stress
in the talk was that it's not

00:56:48.010 --> 00:56:50.350
really that you need the
confounders to be balanced

00:56:50.350 --> 00:56:51.850
across racial groups.

00:56:51.850 --> 00:56:55.510
You need them to be balanced
across exposure groups

00:56:55.510 --> 00:56:57.910
within racial groups

00:56:57.910 --> 00:57:00.460
So it's actually
the same assumption

00:57:00.460 --> 00:57:04.440
that we use in our standard
epidemiologic cohort analyses.

00:57:04.440 --> 00:57:06.620
It's no different.

00:57:06.620 --> 00:57:08.050
It's the same thing.

00:57:08.050 --> 00:57:11.710
So in terms of those,
I really just want

00:57:11.710 --> 00:57:13.930
to make sure that the
major risk factors

00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:17.080
for cardiovascular disease
are actually measured well

00:57:17.080 --> 00:57:18.130
among both groups.

00:57:18.130 --> 00:57:23.560
I think the challenges is
finding cohorts or follow-up

00:57:23.560 --> 00:57:28.507
studies where you have adequate
data on all social groups

00:57:28.507 --> 00:57:29.590
that you're interested in.

00:57:29.590 --> 00:57:31.090
I think that's the challenge.

00:57:31.090 --> 00:57:32.502
- Yep.

00:57:32.502 --> 00:57:33.002
Yep.

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:40.180
- Hi.

00:57:40.180 --> 00:57:42.220
I have a question for
Dr. Jackson as well.

00:57:42.220 --> 00:57:45.880
So again, like with unmeasured
confounding and everything

00:57:45.880 --> 00:57:47.780
like that, and I was--

00:57:47.780 --> 00:57:49.870
kept thinking about
the first example

00:57:49.870 --> 00:57:53.400
you gave about depression
and clinical need.

00:57:53.400 --> 00:57:55.630
I guess like every
disparity that you

00:57:55.630 --> 00:57:57.730
see doesn't necessarily
mean necessarily

00:57:57.730 --> 00:58:00.610
like a difference
in people getting

00:58:00.610 --> 00:58:02.880
what they need
essentially when it comes

00:58:02.880 --> 00:58:04.150
between blacks and whites.

00:58:04.150 --> 00:58:05.380
But I think--

00:58:05.380 --> 00:58:08.140
I guess I would push on
that, because when it comes--

00:58:08.140 --> 00:58:10.000
I mean, isn't that
still a symptom

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:12.020
of disparities in,
say, health care?

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:14.110
So just because there's
a higher prevalence

00:58:14.110 --> 00:58:16.130
in, say, depression among--

00:58:16.130 --> 00:58:18.970
or at least clinical depression
among whites, I mean,

00:58:18.970 --> 00:58:21.970
does that still mean that
there can still potentially

00:58:21.970 --> 00:58:25.060
be the same level prevalence
of depression in blacks

00:58:25.060 --> 00:58:27.309
or even more so, but
it's because of stigma

00:58:27.309 --> 00:58:29.600
in mental health in the
community and things like that,

00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:31.540
and also barriers
to health care.

00:58:31.540 --> 00:58:34.120
That's like another unmeasured
thing we're not looking at.

00:58:34.120 --> 00:58:36.450
So even if you do a condition
on it in your analysis,

00:58:36.450 --> 00:58:39.100
it doesn't necessarily
account for it.

00:58:39.100 --> 00:58:40.690
- Well, there's a lot there.

00:58:40.690 --> 00:58:43.480
I think-- so there are--

00:58:43.480 --> 00:58:47.590
so in the Psych EPU literature,
you see a couple of things.

00:58:47.590 --> 00:58:51.370
Like, you see a lower prevalence
of both current and lifetime

00:58:51.370 --> 00:58:55.840
depression among blacks, but
you see a worse prognosis.

00:58:55.840 --> 00:58:58.060
So you see more--

00:58:58.060 --> 00:59:00.700
you see a higher prevalence
of recurrent depression

00:59:00.700 --> 00:59:04.240
and also chronic
forms of depression,

00:59:04.240 --> 00:59:07.480
and you see poorer function.

00:59:07.480 --> 00:59:09.160
So I'm not--

00:59:09.160 --> 00:59:14.180
I think if you are
thinking about clinical--

00:59:14.180 --> 00:59:15.680
once you condition
on clinical need,

00:59:15.680 --> 00:59:18.502
I'm not sure that you're
missing disparities in treatment

00:59:18.502 --> 00:59:20.960
if you're talking about people
who are showing up initially

00:59:20.960 --> 00:59:25.450
on a first episode, or if
it's a recurrent episode.

00:59:25.450 --> 00:59:29.180
I'm not sure if I'm answering
your question adequately,

00:59:29.180 --> 00:59:32.790
but I'm not sure how
you would be missing

00:59:32.790 --> 00:59:34.920
the disparity by really--

00:59:34.920 --> 00:59:38.090
so if you think about
a disparate treatment,

00:59:38.090 --> 00:59:42.520
you're saying that people
who need the medication

00:59:42.520 --> 00:59:46.040
are getting it less
often than someone who's

00:59:46.040 --> 00:59:48.760
in all other instances
clinically like them

00:59:48.760 --> 00:59:50.280
but of a different race.

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:52.990
And the key issues
with that is that they

00:59:52.990 --> 00:59:55.430
both need the medication.

00:59:55.430 --> 00:59:57.670
Whether or not--
there's a lot of debate

00:59:57.670 --> 01:00:00.591
about our estimates in the
psychiatric epidemiology

01:00:00.591 --> 01:00:01.090
studies.

01:00:01.090 --> 01:00:03.160
Is it because of selection bias?

01:00:03.160 --> 01:00:05.620
There's a large chunks of the
African-American population

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:08.500
missing from household surveys.

01:00:08.500 --> 01:00:11.560
Is it because of
differences in how

01:00:11.560 --> 01:00:15.640
people are answering
the tools that we use

01:00:15.640 --> 01:00:16.840
to measure depression?

01:00:16.840 --> 01:00:20.410
Is it because of differences in
reporting to somatic symptoms

01:00:20.410 --> 01:00:24.160
versus more
psychological symptoms?

01:00:24.160 --> 01:00:28.840
But none of those
alternate explanations

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:31.030
have been compelling, at
least up to this point.

01:00:31.030 --> 01:00:36.610
So most people believe
estimates that the prevalence

01:00:36.610 --> 01:00:39.670
of major depression is, in fact,
lower among African-Americans

01:00:39.670 --> 01:00:41.770
So really the
disparities in treatment

01:00:41.770 --> 01:00:44.192
should really be conditional
on clinical need.

01:00:53.960 --> 01:00:57.730
- Sonya, something that you
put up during your talk really

01:00:57.730 --> 01:01:02.710
resonated with me, and that's
the notion of epidemiologists

01:01:02.710 --> 01:01:05.030
communicating with
non-epidemiologists,

01:01:05.030 --> 01:01:08.470
which is the focus
of this session here.

01:01:08.470 --> 01:01:10.960
And I'd love for both
of you to reflect

01:01:10.960 --> 01:01:13.930
on that, because I felt
like in my training,

01:01:13.930 --> 01:01:16.630
I wasn't trained
on how to do that.

01:01:16.630 --> 01:01:19.900
I can write a scientific
article like nobody's business,

01:01:19.900 --> 01:01:23.120
but I can't communicate
with the public.

01:01:23.120 --> 01:01:28.210
And yet so many of our public
health messages are known.

01:01:28.210 --> 01:01:29.640
Like, people know wear a condom.

01:01:29.640 --> 01:01:31.660
People know get vaccinated.

01:01:31.660 --> 01:01:34.800
And our approach-- my
impression of our approach

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:40.550
has just been to lambaste the
public with more and more data.

01:01:40.550 --> 01:01:43.420
But so-- is it a
function of our training?

01:01:43.420 --> 01:01:45.730
Like, how do you think
we can go about doing

01:01:45.730 --> 01:01:46.911
a better job of this?

01:01:50.577 --> 01:01:51.910
- You know, this is a tough one.

01:01:51.910 --> 01:01:57.210
I think-- I don't know.

01:01:57.210 --> 01:01:59.322
Part of it's a challenge
of just the history

01:01:59.322 --> 01:02:00.780
of how we've
conducted the science,

01:02:00.780 --> 01:02:03.390
and that I think earlier
on we were really getting

01:02:03.390 --> 01:02:04.840
at just pure associations.

01:02:04.840 --> 01:02:06.900
And so we've really
trained the public

01:02:06.900 --> 01:02:11.100
to view a risk factor as
sort of being associated

01:02:11.100 --> 01:02:16.800
with a disease, but maybe
not necessarily thinking

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:20.250
through in terms of gradations
about the particular type

01:02:20.250 --> 01:02:22.790
of question that we're asking.

01:02:22.790 --> 01:02:25.450
So, for instance,
duration of exposure

01:02:25.450 --> 01:02:30.651
to a particular risk factor
or among a certain subgroup.

01:02:30.651 --> 01:02:32.650
I'm not sure I actually
have an answer for that.

01:02:32.650 --> 01:02:35.980
I mean, part of it has to do
with the state of our science

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:38.410
when it goes out to
the public, and how

01:02:38.410 --> 01:02:40.600
much control we have over
that to actually build

01:02:40.600 --> 01:02:41.740
in qualifiers.

01:02:44.590 --> 01:02:45.764
I'm not sure I have--

01:02:45.764 --> 01:02:47.430
to be honest, I just
don't have a good--

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:49.950
it's a problem, I
think, in that we

01:02:49.950 --> 01:02:52.230
have a lot of
over-interpretation

01:02:52.230 --> 01:02:54.750
of our scientific results.

01:02:54.750 --> 01:02:57.240
I think most people,
when you explain

01:02:57.240 --> 01:02:59.340
the limitations of
epidemiology in terms

01:02:59.340 --> 01:03:01.120
of trying to make
fair comparisons,

01:03:01.120 --> 01:03:05.920
most people really
do understand that.

01:03:05.920 --> 01:03:13.650
But in terms of communicating
really finely detailed

01:03:13.650 --> 01:03:18.000
granular answers to
questions, I'm not sure

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:22.342
that we're really there yet.

01:03:22.342 --> 01:03:23.300
- Yeah.

01:03:23.300 --> 01:03:26.630
I'd probably echo
some of that that--

01:03:26.630 --> 01:03:28.310
I think of--
certainly like when I

01:03:28.310 --> 01:03:31.750
talk to my parents or
non-epidemiologists

01:03:31.750 --> 01:03:35.330
in my friendship
or family circles.

01:03:35.330 --> 01:03:39.080
Everyone is very trained to
know that correlation is not

01:03:39.080 --> 01:03:39.960
causation, right?

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:41.320
And that that's like--

01:03:41.320 --> 01:03:44.240
we get that from a high
school statistics course

01:03:44.240 --> 01:03:46.950
or middle school science class.

01:03:46.950 --> 01:03:52.160
And I think that's built
as this level of skepticism

01:03:52.160 --> 01:03:54.290
where you can just kind
of pick the studies you

01:03:54.290 --> 01:03:57.947
want to believe if they support
your beliefs about the world.

01:03:57.947 --> 01:04:00.530
And I think maybe something the
epidemiologist could do better

01:04:00.530 --> 01:04:03.740
is try to train people
to think through how

01:04:03.740 --> 01:04:05.510
if our question
really is causal.

01:04:05.510 --> 01:04:07.880
If I'm trying to decide,
should I take that treatment

01:04:07.880 --> 01:04:11.630
or should I recommend
this change in the schools

01:04:11.630 --> 01:04:13.940
or change in my
hospital policies

01:04:13.940 --> 01:04:18.830
or whatever it might be, how
can I support that empirically,

01:04:18.830 --> 01:04:20.390
and how can I
understand really what

01:04:20.390 --> 01:04:24.110
the assumptions are underlying
that empirical estimate?

01:04:24.110 --> 01:04:26.750
I'm not sure if that can
happen in high schools.

01:04:26.750 --> 01:04:29.660
I don't know if that's just--
when we convey our studies

01:04:29.660 --> 01:04:32.510
to really be transparent about
all the assumptions upon which

01:04:32.510 --> 01:04:34.070
they rest, because
maybe that just

01:04:34.070 --> 01:04:35.810
makes more skeptics
about it because they

01:04:35.810 --> 01:04:36.860
are strong assumptions.

01:04:36.860 --> 01:04:40.340
But I think that's probably
where I would start

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:44.450
is just trying to revisit that
when our question is causal,

01:04:44.450 --> 01:04:46.820
we should be explicit
that that's the question

01:04:46.820 --> 01:04:49.897
and then how confident
we are in those answers.

01:04:49.897 --> 01:04:51.230
- If I could add one more thing.

01:04:51.230 --> 01:04:53.650
I think what would be--

01:04:53.650 --> 01:04:56.300
in addition to what
Sonya talked about--

01:04:56.300 --> 01:04:58.110
would be really
helpful is perhaps

01:04:58.110 --> 01:05:00.140
as epidemiologists
instead of saying

01:05:00.140 --> 01:05:01.940
what the question
has answered, maybe

01:05:01.940 --> 01:05:03.630
list out what it
hasn't answered.

01:05:03.630 --> 01:05:04.130
- Yeah.

01:05:04.130 --> 01:05:05.600
- So for a lot of
medications, we

01:05:05.600 --> 01:05:08.550
don't have data
on long term use.

01:05:08.550 --> 01:05:12.260
So for psychotropics, what's
the actual effectiveness

01:05:12.260 --> 01:05:14.870
five years out, six
years out, 10 years out?

01:05:14.870 --> 01:05:17.542
Do we actually have
good data on that?

01:05:17.542 --> 01:05:20.000
I think a lot of times when
we're thinking about these risk

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:22.149
factors or things
that we encounter,

01:05:22.149 --> 01:05:23.690
there are certain
assumptions that we

01:05:23.690 --> 01:05:25.356
make about how we're
using them and what

01:05:25.356 --> 01:05:28.920
the risks are without
any data to support that.

01:05:28.920 --> 01:05:32.690
So I think pointing out
perhaps what the questions are

01:05:32.690 --> 01:05:34.970
that aren't being answered.

01:05:34.970 --> 01:05:37.179
If we list those all
along with the question

01:05:37.179 --> 01:05:38.720
that we did answer,
it would probably

01:05:38.720 --> 01:05:44.300
help frame what we know
and what we don't know.

01:05:44.300 --> 01:05:47.030
- Maybe just one other
thing I would add just

01:05:47.030 --> 01:05:50.000
thinking about this more
is among epidemiologists,

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:52.610
I think we're good at doing
sensitivity analyses to try

01:05:52.610 --> 01:05:54.860
to understand how robust
our conclusions are,

01:05:54.860 --> 01:05:57.560
but that could be communicated
better as well, right?

01:05:57.560 --> 01:06:02.070
There's a lot of times
that we show something

01:06:02.070 --> 01:06:03.800
and we say there's
an effect, and then

01:06:03.800 --> 01:06:05.630
that makes some New
York Times headline

01:06:05.630 --> 01:06:09.200
and it gets lost in the noise
of how confident we are in that.

01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:12.020
But, I mean, we're confident
that vaccines save lives.

01:06:12.020 --> 01:06:14.990
We're confident that
vaccines do not cause autism.

01:06:14.990 --> 01:06:16.730
That smoking causes lung cancer.

01:06:16.730 --> 01:06:19.820
That safe storage practices
of guns saves lives.

01:06:19.820 --> 01:06:22.310
Like, we know those things,
and we know those things

01:06:22.310 --> 01:06:24.770
because we've done a lot
of sensitivity analyses.

01:06:24.770 --> 01:06:29.061
And I wonder if there's a way
to communicate that better too.

01:06:29.061 --> 01:06:29.561
Yeah.

01:06:34.292 --> 01:06:35.000
- Thank you both.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:37.150
I think just piggybacking
on the conversation

01:06:37.150 --> 01:06:39.980
